ociated with the Transition of Students from Eighth Grade to High School -- t12. Establishing Successful Transitions for Intermediate Students -- t13. Exploring a “Family of Schools” Model for Cross-Panel Mathematics Teacher Professional Development -- t14. The Visual Turn: Transitioning into Visual Approaches to Literacy Education -- t15. Transitioning to Being Bilingual: Examining the Linguistic and Non-linguistic Effects of Brief Bilingual Exchanges -- t16. Aboriginal Education: A Transition of World Views -- tPart IV. Secondary (Grades 9–12) to Postsecondary (College/University) -- t17. Secondary to Postsecondary Transitions -- t18. Student Transitions from Secondary to College Mathematics -- t19. Inspirational Transitions: Cultivating the Capacity to Embrace Technology-Enhanced Learning and Teaching -- tCoda: Supporting Students and Teachers within and across Transitional Spaces -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPerspectives on Transitions in Schooling and Instructional Practice examines student transitions between major levels of schooling, teacher transitions in instructional practice, and the intersection of these two significant themes in education research. Twenty-six leading international experts offer meaningful insights on current pedagogical practices, obstacles to effective transitions, and proven strategies for stakeholders involved in supporting students in transition.The book is divided into four sections, representing the four main transitions in formal schooling: Early Years (Home, Pre-school, and Kindergarten) to Early Elementary (Grades 1–3); Early Elementary to Late Elementary (Grades 4–8); Late Elementary to Secondary (Grades 9–12); and Secondary to Post-Secondary (College and University). A coda draws together over-arching themes from throughout the text to provide recommendations and a visual model that captures their interactions.Combining theoretical approaches with practical examples of school-based initiatives, this book will appeal to those involved in supporting either the student experience (both academically and emotionally) or teacher professional learning and growth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArticulation (Education). 0aEffective teaching. 0aSchool improvement programs. 0aStudent adjustment. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Psychology.2bisacsh1 aAkos, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBinstadt, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuzza, Dawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByers, Trish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCantalini-Williams, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCartmel, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoate, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott-Johns, Susan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott-Johns, Susan E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFelton, Kelsey Augst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowler, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHachkowski, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHauser, Gregory M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelling, Gianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Amber, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarvis, Daniel H. , eeditor.